    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2555786772" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2555786772" />
    <a title="Laura Dahlman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/87599597-laura-dahlman"><img alt="Laura Dahlman" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2555786772?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura Dahlman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura Dahlman" href="/user/show/87599597-laura-dahlman">Laura Dahlman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2555786772" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11453587484090285433"> There is a smattering of good advice in here but it gets lost in the dated and out of touch cartoons and advice, this book did not age very well. The advice waffles between mindfulness and the law of attraction which, although often shoehorned together, are in my opinion oil and water. This book brought to mind a pyramid scheme sales pitch or a cringey motivational speaker you&apos;d be forced to listen to at work. Work REALLY REALLY REALLY hard and don&apos;t EVER complain or ask any questions and you&apos;l</span>
  <span id="freeText11453587484090285433" style="display:none"> There is a smattering of good advice in here but it gets lost in the dated and out of touch cartoons and advice, this book did not age very well. The advice waffles between mindfulness and the law of attraction which, although often shoehorned together, are in my opinion oil and water. This book brought to mind a pyramid scheme sales pitch or a cringey motivational speaker you'd be forced to listen to at work. Work REALLY REALLY REALLY hard and don't EVER complain or ask any questions and you'll be rewarded for your efforts we promise. Let's just stuff all those "bad/negative" emotions down and pretend like they don't exist because if we talk about them you might catch "negativity" like it's the flu or something and you might be sad and no one wants to be around a sad person, remember HAPPY HAPPY HAPPY it's the only acceptable way to be so force a smile on your face and when someone says jump your enthusiastic response is always how high.<br /> As I said there were bits and pieces of good advice in here such as you can't run from your problems as they tend to follow you wherever you go (although depends on the problem sometimes running is exactly what you need to do). The importance of just starting somewhere rather than getting overwhelmed by the big picture, and being patient results aren't instantaneous. Overall though this book is a waste of time and there are vastly better books out there which take reality into consideration that are much more deserving of your time.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11453587484090285433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

